ðŸ”Œ Wiring Guide â€“ DIY Sim Racing OLED Dash

This document explains how to wire the SH1106 OLED display and button to an Arduino UNO R4 for the Sim Racing Telemetry Dash project.

ðŸ§  Hardware Required

Arduino UNO R4

SH1106 128x64 SPI OLED Display

1x Push Button (momentary)

Jumper wires

Breadboard (optional)

ðŸ–¥ OLED Wiring (SPI Mode)

âš  IMPORTANT:
Your OLED must be configured in SPI mode, NOT I2C.

Pin Connections
OLED Pin	Connect To (UNO R4)
VCC	5V
GND	GND
SCK	Pin 13
SDA (MOSI)	Pin 11
CS	Pin 10
DC	Pin 9
RES (RST)	Pin 8

ðŸ”˜ Mode Toggle Button Wiring

The button is used to toggle display modes.

Button Side	Connect To
One side	GND
Other side	Pin 2

No external resistor required.

The firmware uses the internal pull-up resistor:

pinMode(BUTTON_PIN, INPUT_PULLUP);

This means:

Button pressed â†’ LOW

Button released â†’ HIGH

The Arduino UNO R4 provides sufficient 5V power for the OLED.

If you experience flickering:

Check ground connection

Shorten SPI wires

Ensure secure breadboard contacts

ðŸ§ª Troubleshooting

Screen Is Blank

Confirm OLED is set to SPI mode

Verify wiring matches table above

Confirm correct constructor in firmware:

U8G2_SH1106_128X64_NONAME_F_4W_HW_SPI u8g2(U8G2_R0, 10, 9, 8);

Confirm Serial Monitor baud rate is 115200


Button Not Working

Confirm one side is connected to GND

Confirm other side is connected to Pin 2

Verify firmware uses INPUT_PULLUP

Display Shows Random Pixels / Glitches

Keep SPI wires short

Avoid running wires near power supply lines

Ensure solid ground connection


ðŸ“¡ Required Telemetry Format

The firmware expects serial data formatted like this:

RPM:12345 MAX:13000 GEAR:3 DRS:0 PIT:0

Sent at:

115200 baud

If using SimHub or custom telemetry software, ensure this format matches exactly.
